Here's how to save/restore draft text using MAUI's lifecycle events:

**1. Override lifecycle methods in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.SaveDraft();
        };

        window.Activated += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.RestoreDraft();
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. Implement save/restore in your page:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Preferences.ContainsKey(DraftKey))
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Clear draft when user explicitly saves
    private void OnSaveClicked(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // ... your save logic ...
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to background — save here
- **`Window.Activated`** fires when returning to foreground — restore here
- **`Preferences`** persists small strings across app restarts (uses `SharedPreferences` on Android, `NSUserDefaults` on iOS)
- For larger drafts, use `SecureStorage` or write to `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory`
